  • Suppressing setup code and output

Suppressing setup code and output

Case study: loading tidyverse

If you try to load the tidyverse package, you get many messages.

library(tidyverse)
## ── Attaching packages ────────────────────────────── tidyverse 1.2.1 ──
## ✔ ggplot2 3.2.1     ✔ purrr   0.3.2
## ✔ tibble  2.1.3     ✔ dplyr   0.8.3
## ✔ tidyr   1.0.0     ✔ stringr 1.4.0
## ✔ readr   1.3.1     ✔ forcats 0.4.0
## ── Conflicts ───────────────────────────────── tidyverse_conflicts() ──
## ✖ dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
## ✖ dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()

In writing your report, it is most likely undesirable that it

  1. prints your the R code; and
  2. has all the messages printed.

If you have the chunk with eval = FALSE then it will not print those messages but it will not evaluate the R code within the chunk.

You can see this if we first unload the ggplot2 pacakge that was loaded with tidyverse previously:

detach("package:ggplot2", unload = TRUE)

then try to load the package but without evaluating the code within the chunk:

library(tidyverse)

and try to run ggplot function

ggplot(cars, aes(dist, speed)) +
  geom_point()
## Error in ggplot(cars, aes(dist, speed)): could not find function "ggplot"

we get an error! This is because the chunk to load the tidyverse was not evaluated.

What you want to do is to suppress the code and for this you can use echo = FALSE.
